00:24:36.668 --> 00:24:38.586
Okay, good,
if you could tilt it up


492
00:24:38.628 --> 00:24:40.255
towards the Christmas tree.

493
00:24:40.296 --> 00:24:41.798
Yeah.

494
00:24:41.840 --> 00:24:45.093
Okay. Good. Perfect.

495
00:24:45.134 --> 00:24:46.845
Caption time.

496
00:24:46.886 --> 00:24:49.889
I need to find a pen.
Gotta brainstorm.


497
00:24:49.931 --> 00:24:52.433
Oh, Amelia, not on any
of the mayor's important stuff.


498
00:24:52.475 --> 00:24:53.685
Wait, wait, wait!

499
00:24:53.726 --> 00:24:56.020
- Mayor Thomas.
- Yes.


500
00:24:56.062 --> 00:24:58.106
Mayor Thomas,
this is Campbell Wallace.


501
00:24:58.147 --> 00:25:00.316
She's doing the article
about Pere Noel.


502
00:25:00.358 --> 00:25:01.776
Oh, okay.

503
00:25:01.818 --> 00:25:03.903
The mayor
and Everett go way back.


504
00:25:03.945 --> 00:25:05.422
Campbell,
it's a pleasure to meet you.


505
00:25:05.446 --> 00:25:08.616
- And welcome to Sorrento!
- Thank you. Nice to be here.


506
00:25:08.658 --> 00:25:12.871
Absolutely. You know, I think
she should meet Jackson Shepherd.


507
00:25:12.912 --> 00:25:14.956
I think he'd be
a great resource for you.


508
00:25:14.998 --> 00:25:17.542
Actually, she's staying
at his family's cottage.


509
00:25:17.584 --> 00:25:20.003
Ah, there you go.
Meant to be.


510
00:25:20.044 --> 00:25:22.630
He's around here somewhere.

511
00:25:22.672 --> 00:25:24.424
Hey, Jackson!

512
00:25:26.509 --> 00:25:28.011
Come over here!

513
00:25:31.014 --> 00:25:33.391
Jackson Shepherd,
this is Campbell Wallace.


514
00:25:33.433 --> 00:25:35.810
She's the reporter
from the travel magazine.


515
00:25:35.852 --> 00:25:37.520
Ah. Well, <i>bonjour,</i>miss.

516
00:25:37.562 --> 00:25:39.814
<i>Bonjour</i> indeed.

517
00:25:39.856 --> 00:25:42.525
Oh, Mayor Thomas, if you're
wondering why the present I got you


518
00:25:42.567 --> 00:25:46.988
is broken into a million pieces,
that's because of her.


519
00:25:47.030 --> 00:25:49.741
Well, Campbell,
you can ask this rude young man


520
00:25:49.782 --> 00:25:51.993
anything about anything,
he knows it all.


521
00:25:52.035 --> 00:25:53.995
He's the keeper
of all the town records


522
00:25:54.037 --> 00:25:55.705
and he helps us out
when we have visitors.


523
00:25:55.747 --> 00:25:56.998
- Great.
- Okay.


524
00:25:57.040 --> 00:25:58.392
I just hope I don't
ruin your flow,


525
00:25:58.416 --> 00:25:59.918
what with me
being a tourist, and all.


526
00:25:59.959 --> 00:26:02.003
Well, it was her who started.

527
00:26:02.045 --> 00:26:04.506
I mean, I feel like you
started that before.


528
00:26:04.547 --> 00:26:06.633
- And you'll be staying at the cottage?
- Yeah.


529
00:26:06.674 --> 00:26:09.552
- Excellent.
- I can't tell if they're flirting or fighting.


530
00:26:09.594 --> 00:26:12.138
- Maybe both.
- That's why I put her in the cottage.


531
00:26:12.180 --> 00:26:13.848
You're good with people,
you know that?


532
00:26:13.890 --> 00:26:15.642
Well, it's a gift.
What can I say?


533
00:26:17.644 --> 00:26:20.688
So, Jennifer, I wanted to ask,

534
00:26:20.730 --> 00:26:23.358
what's Everett like, to you?

535
00:26:23.399 --> 00:26:25.109
Um, well...

536
00:26:25.151 --> 00:26:27.320
he's smart and hard-working.

537
00:26:27.362 --> 00:26:29.155
And loving.

538
00:26:29.197 --> 00:26:30.532
Um...

539
00:26:30.573 --> 00:26:32.200
You know, when I met him,

540
00:26:32.242 --> 00:26:35.411
he had just pulled himself
out of a really dark place.


541
00:26:35.453 --> 00:26:41.209
And he's spent the rest of his life
trying to do better, be better.


542
00:26:41.251 --> 00:26:45.463
There's not a lot of people
you can say that about.


543
00:26:45.505 --> 00:26:48.883
And, you know,
he makes me laugh... a lot.


544
00:26:48.925 --> 00:26:52.345
Tsk... I think
I just love him to bits.


545
00:26:52.387 --> 00:26:56.516
Yeah, see, I wish I could
see him the way all of you do.


546
00:26:56.558 --> 00:26:59.602
And I wish he could have been
those things for me.


547
00:27:00.728 --> 00:27:02.397
- Hey!
- Hey.


548
00:27:02.438 --> 00:27:03.731
Perfect timing.

549
00:27:03.773 --> 00:27:05.567
I just set out
the last batch to cool.


550
00:27:05.608 --> 00:27:07.026
- Good day?
- Excellent.


551
00:27:07.068 --> 00:27:08.570
I'm thinking of hiring Campbell.

552
00:27:08.611 --> 00:27:11.030
She's a perfect fit
for our little operation here.


553
00:27:11.072 --> 00:27:12.740
- Okay.
- How was your day?


554
00:27:12.782 --> 00:27:14.909
Well, much better
now that you're here.


555
00:27:14.951 --> 00:27:16.327
- Oh.
- Come on, let's eat.


556
00:27:16.369 --> 00:27:18.097
- Well, well, well, okay.
- You too, Campbell.


557
00:27:18.121 --> 00:27:20.915
- Campbell. Come on now.
- Yep.


558
00:27:20.957 --> 00:27:22.917
All right.
Ooh, something smells good.


559
00:27:22.959 --> 00:27:25.920
- Mmm.
- Girls, come on, dinner!


560
00:27:25.962 --> 00:27:29.215
I'm just gonna grab my things
and head out.


561
00:27:29.257 --> 00:27:31.551
You can't leave yet.
Stay for dinner.


562
00:27:31.593 --> 00:27:33.344
Look, there's plenty of food.

563
00:27:33.386 --> 00:27:36.097
I just... I should really get
started on writing my article,


564
00:27:36.139 --> 00:27:38.516
and I don't want to intrude
on family time.


565
00:27:38.558 --> 00:27:40.977
Guess what? After dinner,
we're making wreaths.


566
00:27:41.019 --> 00:27:43.438
It's a family tradition
on the first night off school.


567
00:27:43.479 --> 00:27:45.374
- You can sit by me.
- Uh-uh, she's sitting by me.


568
00:27:45.398 --> 00:27:47.108
We're going
to talk about photography.


569
00:27:47.150 --> 00:27:50.028
Sounds like the girls
already saved a spot for you.


570
00:27:50.069 --> 00:27:52.447
Now, look, this article
is about me, right?


571
00:27:52.489 --> 00:27:54.699
Well, to know my family
<i>is</i> to know me.


572
00:27:56.951 --> 00:27:58.203
Why don't you stay awhile?

573
00:27:59.537 --> 00:28:01.039
How can I say no?

574
00:28:02.999 --> 00:28:04.599
You can just put your stuff
on the chair.


575
00:28:04.626 --> 00:28:05.835
Thank you.

576
00:28:05.877 --> 00:28:08.213
- Mm-mm. Who's first?
- Smells good.


577
00:28:08.254 --> 00:28:09.756
For you.

578
00:28:17.305 --> 00:28:21.351
"This will be
your best Christmas ever."


579
00:28:21.392 --> 00:28:24.395
Hi, Mom.

580
00:28:24.437 --> 00:28:26.272
<i>Hey, baby.
How are you holding up?</i>


581
00:28:26.314 --> 00:28:28.525
Uh... getting settled in.

582
00:28:28.566 --> 00:28:30.443
You know, meeting my father
for the first time,


583
00:28:30.485 --> 00:28:32.445
not telling him
I'm his daughter.


584
00:28:32.487 --> 00:28:35.156
- You haven't told him yet?
<i>- I panicked.</i>


585
00:28:35.198 --> 00:28:37.575
Well, that's totally normal,
sweetheart.


586
00:28:37.617 --> 00:28:38.868
<i>It still feels weird.</i>

587
00:28:38.910 --> 00:28:40.453
It's kind of like lying,
you know?


588
00:28:40.495 --> 00:28:43.289
I mean, it's...
a lot like lying.


589
00:28:43.331 --> 00:28:45.792
<i>Well, it's also a way
of keeping yourself safe</i>


590
00:28:45.834 --> 00:28:47.877
and get to know him better.

591
00:28:47.919 --> 00:28:49.170
How are the girls?

592
00:28:49.212 --> 00:28:50.797
Oh, Mom, they're amazing.

593
00:28:50.839 --> 00:28:53.716
I mean, Amelia is so spunky,

594
00:28:53.758 --> 00:28:57.136
and Mary-Margaret
is just such a moody teenager.


595
00:28:57.178 --> 00:28:59.764
You know, she's trying
to be real cool.


596
00:28:59.806 --> 00:29:02.600
She just, like, reminds me a lot
of myself when I was that age.


597
00:29:02.642 --> 00:29:05.103
And last night we were making
wreaths, and, um...


598
00:29:06.521 --> 00:29:08.815
Oh, hang on, Mom.
Someone's at my door.


599
00:29:08.857 --> 00:29:10.942
It's okay. Go.
Just call me later.


600
00:29:10.984 --> 00:29:12.068
I love you!

601
00:29:12.110 --> 00:29:13.361
Love you.

602
00:29:17.323 --> 00:29:21.619
Well, look who
the reindeer dragged in.


603
00:29:21.661 --> 00:29:23.830
Pere Noel doesn't
actually have reindeer.


604
00:29:23.872 --> 00:29:25.582
Oh, yeah?
What does he use, then?


605
00:29:25.623 --> 00:29:27.041
Alligators.

606
00:29:27.083 --> 00:29:29.961
Oh. The Ayutthaya province
has elephants,


607
00:29:30.003 --> 00:29:33.798
the North Pole has reindeers, and Cajun
country has alligators, naturally.


608
00:29:38.011 --> 00:29:39.470
Oh, right. Sorry.

609
00:29:39.512 --> 00:29:41.973
Uh, so, your coffee machine
here is broken,


610
00:29:42.015 --> 00:29:43.683
so I brought you this.

611
00:29:43.725 --> 00:29:45.435
My grandma's recipe.

612
00:29:45.476 --> 00:29:47.478
I hope you like
Cajun eggnog flavor.


613
00:29:47.520 --> 00:29:49.105
Cajun eggnog. Never had it.

614
00:29:49.147 --> 00:29:51.566
Ah. That's a point for me then.

615
00:29:51.608 --> 00:29:53.502
I mean, essentially
it's eggnog instead of creamer,


616
00:29:53.526 --> 00:29:56.279
with nutmeg, cinnamon, cayenne,

617
00:29:56.321 --> 00:29:58.114
and a little
imitation rum extract.


618
00:29:58.156 --> 00:30:00.116
Sounds different.

619
00:30:00.158 --> 00:30:02.160
It's a southern
Louisiana tradition, so...


620
00:30:02.202 --> 00:30:03.661
Mmm, don't worry,
I love different.


621
00:30:03.703 --> 00:30:06.998
Believe me, in my line of work,
I get plenty of it.


622
00:30:07.040 --> 00:30:09.417
- Ever had mopane?
- I have not.


623
00:30:09.459 --> 00:30:12.003
- What is that?
- Worms.


624
00:30:12.045 --> 00:30:14.005
It's a Zimbabwean
Christmas tradition.


625
00:30:14.047 --> 00:30:16.299
That sounds... delicious.

626
00:30:16.341 --> 00:30:18.593
It's actually pretty good.
Almost as good as this coffee.


627
00:30:18.635 --> 00:30:20.178
Glad to hear it.

628
00:30:20.220 --> 00:30:22.597
Hey, I was thinking,
maybe I'd take you on a tour?


629
00:30:22.639 --> 00:30:25.350
You can see the sights.
I mean, it's no Zimbabwe...


630
00:30:25.391 --> 00:30:27.519
Actually, I'm tailing
Everett today,


631
00:30:27.560 --> 00:30:30.188
Pere Noel duties,
but maybe you could help me


632
00:30:30.230 --> 00:30:31.606
do some research after lunch?

633
00:30:31.648 --> 00:30:33.942
Sorrento's resident geek
is at your service.


634
00:30:33.983 --> 00:30:35.860
Great, it's a date then.

635
00:30:35.902 --> 00:30:37.195
Um...

636
00:30:37.237 --> 00:30:38.488
Yeah, cheers.

637
00:30:38.530 --> 00:30:39.739
Cheers.

638
00:30:44.410 --> 00:30:46.579
You know, it's a great honor
to take on the mantle


639
00:30:46.621 --> 00:30:48.289
of Pere Noel from Shepherd here,

640
00:30:48.331 --> 00:30:51.167
who's had that distinction
for nearly 30 years.


641
00:30:53.086 --> 00:30:56.798
Now, as my first official act
as Sorrento's new Pere Noel,


642
00:30:56.840 --> 00:31:00.552
I'm going to hang the first
ornament on the town tree,


643
00:31:00.593 --> 00:31:03.596
as a sign that Christmas
is just around the corner.


644
00:31:06.432 --> 00:31:09.435
Hey, you know,
this is the time of year


645
00:31:09.477 --> 00:31:12.397
where we're supposed to be the
most hospitable and welcoming,


646
00:31:12.438 --> 00:31:14.899
so I'd like to ask
somebody else to help me.


647
00:31:14.941 --> 00:31:19.070
Kind of an honorary Pere Noel
assistant for the season.


648
00:31:19.112 --> 00:31:21.573
Campbell Wallace.
What do you say?


649
00:31:21.614 --> 00:31:22.949
- Uh...
- Go on!


650
00:31:22.991 --> 00:31:24.325
Okay, sure.

651
00:31:24.367 --> 00:31:25.493
- Thank you.
- Anywhere.


652
00:31:25.535 --> 00:31:27.078
- Right here? Yeah?
- Yep.


653
00:31:27.120 --> 00:31:29.289
- Okay.
- There we go. Ta-da!


654
00:31:31.416 --> 00:31:33.001
You didn't have to do that.

655
00:31:33.042 --> 00:31:34.544
Of course I did.
You're our guest.


656
00:31:34.586 --> 00:31:36.462
All right, folks join in!

657
00:31:52.729 --> 00:31:57.192
"Mo' fassa and fassa,
da gator dey came!"


658
00:31:57.233 --> 00:32:01.488
"He whistle and holla
and called dem by name!"


659
00:32:01.529 --> 00:32:04.949
Hey, now, kids,
we have a special visitor,


660
00:32:04.991 --> 00:32:07.994
coming all the way from the
magical land of Dallas, Texas.


661
00:32:08.036 --> 00:32:09.454
- Oooh!
- Now, I reckon she's never


662
00:32:09.496 --> 00:32:11.706
even heard this story before,
have you?


663
00:32:11.748 --> 00:32:14.209
I can't say that I have.
Not this version, anyway.


664
00:32:14.250 --> 00:32:18.713
Well then, she doesn't even know
the names of Pere Noel's gators.


665
00:32:18.755 --> 00:32:21.132
Should we teach her? Y'all
want to practice your reading?


666
00:32:21.174 --> 00:32:22.509
Yeah!

667
00:32:22.550 --> 00:32:23.885
All right, come on up here.

668
00:32:23.927 --> 00:32:25.595
- Let's do it.
- Okay.


669
00:32:27.639 --> 00:32:29.641
- Right here. You ready?
- Okay.


670
00:32:29.682 --> 00:32:30.475
Here we go.

671
00:32:30.517 --> 00:32:33.811
"Ha, Gaston! Ha, Tiboy!"

672
00:32:33.853 --> 00:32:36.272
"Ha, Pierre an' Alcee!"

673
00:32:36.314 --> 00:32:38.900
"Gee, Ninette! Gee, Suzette!"

674
00:32:38.942 --> 00:32:41.694
"Celeste an' Renee!"

675
00:32:44.447 --> 00:32:46.342
- Not my best performance.
- Oh, that's all right.


676
00:32:46.366 --> 00:32:48.368
Look, that's for you.
Now you can practice.


677
00:32:48.409 --> 00:32:50.995
That's how you get ahold
of Pere Noel on Christmas Eve.


678
00:32:51.037 --> 00:32:53.748
- Thank you.
- And remember your time down here.


679
00:32:53.790 --> 00:32:56.084
All right, now, kids,
how does the story end?


680
00:32:56.125 --> 00:32:58.294
"Merry Christmas to all,

681
00:32:58.336 --> 00:33:01.005
'til I saw you some mo'!"

682
00:33:01.047 --> 00:33:03.258
All right.

683
00:33:03.299 --> 00:33:05.885
Hey, hot chocolate
right over here.


684
00:33:05.927 --> 00:33:08.012
Oooh!

685
00:33:08.054 --> 00:33:09.514
Hi there.

686
00:33:13.518 --> 00:33:15.144
Come in.

687
00:33:16.479 --> 00:33:19.983
Oh, hey.
Glad you could make it.


688
00:33:20.024 --> 00:33:22.443
Wow... festive.

689
00:33:22.485 --> 00:33:25.155
Yeah, I get pretty focused
on my work.


690
00:33:25.196 --> 00:33:27.699
Yeah, I mean, I get it.
Practical.


691
00:33:27.740 --> 00:33:29.242
Ah, what the Japanese
call <i>shibui.</i>


692
00:33:29.284 --> 00:33:30.493
Boring?

693
00:33:30.535 --> 00:33:33.037
Understated.

694
00:33:33.079 --> 00:33:36.374
Oh, hey. So, the town paper
is doing a series on Everett.


695
00:33:36.416 --> 00:33:38.543
Asked me to pull
all the public files on him,


696
00:33:38.585 --> 00:33:41.671
old articles, government files,
photographs.


697
00:33:41.713 --> 00:33:44.174
So I thought maybe you could
use it for your article as well?


698
00:33:44.215 --> 00:33:46.551
That's incredible.
Yeah, thank you.


699
00:33:46.593 --> 00:33:49.470
Ugh! So... I haven't
looked at it yet, but...


700
00:33:49.512 --> 00:33:51.097
that should keep you busy
for a while.


701
00:33:51.139 --> 00:33:53.808
- Yep.
- Feel free to work here as long as you want.


702
00:33:56.144 --> 00:33:59.814
- You want coffee?
- The answer to that question will always be yes.


703
00:33:59.856 --> 00:34:00.899
Okay.

704
00:34:10.617 --> 00:34:12.410
Hey, you want cream or sugar?

705
00:34:12.452 --> 00:34:15.205
Uh, just coffee is fine,
thank you.


706
00:34:17.832 --> 00:34:19.834
This is from the year he left.

707
00:34:32.138 --> 00:34:33.556
All right, here we go.

708
00:34:33.598 --> 00:34:36.267
So, where should we get started?

709
00:34:36.309 --> 00:34:38.019
Uh, actually, I have to go.

710
00:34:38.061 --> 00:34:40.939
Sorry, my, uh, my editor
needs a progress report,


711
00:34:40.980 --> 00:34:43.399
so I have to go
and upload some pictures.


712
00:34:43.441 --> 00:34:46.486
But thank you, and, um...
I'll call you?


713
00:34:46.528 --> 00:34:48.863
Yep.

714
00:34:50.323 --> 00:34:51.658
Fine.

715
00:35:15.181 --> 00:35:18.101
She told me about you.
Maybe we'll sit down and visit.


716
00:35:18.142 --> 00:35:20.353
She let me know kind of
what's going on...


717
00:35:21.646 --> 00:35:24.107
I figured, look,
this is something


718
00:35:24.148 --> 00:35:26.484
that I know what I'm talking
about 'cause I've been there.


719
00:35:26.526 --> 00:35:28.246
- You've been there?
- Yeah, and back again.


720
00:35:37.537 --> 00:35:39.330
- Hey.
- Hi.


721
00:35:39.372 --> 00:35:41.374
How'd it go with your boss?

722
00:35:41.416 --> 00:35:43.001
Uh, yeah, good, good.
Yeah, uh...


723
00:35:43.042 --> 00:35:44.878
Just, uh...
just, uh, working away.


724
00:35:44.919 --> 00:35:46.379
Great. Do you care
if I sit down?


725
00:35:46.421 --> 00:35:48.548
Sure. Go ahead.

726
00:35:48.590 --> 00:35:49.674
Thank you.

727
00:35:49.716 --> 00:35:51.843
- Hey, um...
- Yeah.


728
00:35:51.885 --> 00:35:54.179
Who is that guy that Everett
is talking to outside?


729
